00:03:19.410 --> 00:03:21.680
CHUO-LING CHANG: So
what is App Streaming?

00:03:21.680 --> 00:03:24.490
To enable this "try
now" experience,

00:03:24.490 --> 00:03:28.130
instead of asking our user
to first wait for a download,

00:03:28.130 --> 00:03:33.240
we actually pre-install the
app in a virtual Android

00:03:33.240 --> 00:03:35.300
device running in the cloud.

00:03:35.300 --> 00:03:38.810
So as soon as the user
clicks on the Try Now button,

00:03:38.810 --> 00:03:44.180
we start again in the cloud,
and the audio and visual content

00:03:44.180 --> 00:03:46.660
generated by the
game is then captured

00:03:46.660 --> 00:03:51.160
and streamed all the way
down to the user's device.

00:03:51.160 --> 00:03:53.270
This is similar to how
videos are streamed

00:03:53.270 --> 00:03:55.750
on services like YouTube.

00:03:55.750 --> 00:04:00.620
And in addition, to let the
user interact with the game,

00:04:00.620 --> 00:04:03.410
we also capture user
controls such as the touch

00:04:03.410 --> 00:04:07.310
gestures, and then stream
them back up to the cloud,

00:04:07.310 --> 00:04:11.680
so that the game can update
its content accordingly.

00:04:11.680 --> 00:04:14.540
This two-way
exchange is carefully

00:04:14.540 --> 00:04:17.060
designed to run fast
and smooth, such

00:04:17.060 --> 00:04:21.029
that the user can enjoy the game
as if it was installed locally

00:04:21.029 --> 00:04:21.760
on the device.

