CHUO-LING CHANG: So
now let's come back

00:12:00.350 --> 00:12:04.420
to talk more about how
App Streaming works.

00:12:07.780 --> 00:12:11.290
First we run an army of
Android virtual machines

00:12:11.290 --> 00:12:14.282
on Google Cloud Platform,
which is Google's public cloud

00:12:14.282 --> 00:12:18.530
offering that is rapidly
expanding around the globe.

00:12:18.530 --> 00:12:20.980
So you can think of these
Android virtual machines

00:12:20.980 --> 00:12:23.030
as running the actual
Android operating

00:12:23.030 --> 00:12:27.070
system on virtualized
CPUs in the cloud.

00:12:27.070 --> 00:12:30.000
And just like the Linux
VMs and Windows VMs

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:32.260
you usually see on
Google Cloud Platform

00:12:32.260 --> 00:12:34.480
or any other
[? elastic ?] clouds,

00:12:34.480 --> 00:12:38.480
these Android VMs can be
quickly spinned up or torn down

00:12:38.480 --> 00:12:39.570
on demand.

00:12:39.570 --> 00:12:41.780
And that is how we
scale App Streaming

00:12:41.780 --> 00:12:42.970
to serve Google users.

00:12:47.300 --> 00:12:50.300
The Android VMs currently
run Android Marshmallow.

00:12:50.300 --> 00:12:52.800
And we regularly
apply system patches

00:12:52.800 --> 00:12:55.740
to make sure that
these games always

00:12:55.740 --> 00:12:58.703
run in up-to-date environments
for best performance.

00:13:03.260 --> 00:13:06.050
Now as you can
imagine, in the cloud

00:13:06.050 --> 00:13:09.350
these Android VMs do not
have physical touch panels

00:13:09.350 --> 00:13:12.310
or physical displays
attached to them.

00:13:12.310 --> 00:13:15.720
In order to support
device input, what we do

00:13:15.720 --> 00:13:19.210
is we customize these
Androids in the [INAUDIBLE]

00:13:19.210 --> 00:13:23.400
abstraction layer so that they
can take virtual input events

00:13:23.400 --> 00:13:25.950
streamed from the
user's physical device

00:13:25.950 --> 00:13:28.880
all the way across the internet.

00:13:28.880 --> 00:13:32.020
And similarly, to
support device output,

00:13:32.020 --> 00:13:34.760
in the VM we capture the
rendering, frame buffer,

00:13:34.760 --> 00:13:38.350
and audio samples and code
them into video bit stream,

00:13:38.350 --> 00:13:39.930
and send it down to the user.

00:13:44.010 --> 00:13:48.470
To deliver a fully
interactive experience,

00:13:48.470 --> 00:13:52.470
this additional two-way latency
introduced by App Streaming

00:13:52.470 --> 00:13:55.350
needs to be as low as possible.

00:13:55.350 --> 00:13:59.030
So we actually spent a lot
of efforts streamlining

00:13:59.030 --> 00:14:02.090
every single component
in this system,

00:14:02.090 --> 00:14:04.030
all the way from
the mobile client,

00:14:04.030 --> 00:14:07.290
the network, and also
the cloud servers.

00:14:07.290 --> 00:14:10.330
In our current implementation,
the processing time

00:14:10.330 --> 00:14:14.300
and buffering time on the client
and on the server combined

00:14:14.300 --> 00:14:17.220
is only 60 milliseconds.

00:14:17.220 --> 00:14:19.880
And in the US, the
network roundtrip time

00:14:19.880 --> 00:14:23.190
from the user to a Google
Call Phone Data Center

00:14:23.190 --> 00:14:27.260
is typically around
20 to 40 milliseconds.

00:14:27.260 --> 00:14:31.340
That means in total, App
Streaming only adds up to 60

00:14:31.340 --> 00:14:36.290
plus 40-- 100
milliseconds of latency.

00:14:36.290 --> 00:14:38.910
That's 1/10 of a second.

00:14:38.910 --> 00:14:41.270
And as you all saw
earlier in the demos,

00:14:41.270 --> 00:14:43.690
this number is low enough
such that we can still

00:14:43.690 --> 00:14:46.845
deliver an enjoyable
mobile gaming experience.

00:14:52.750 --> 00:14:56.690
As you all know, in
streaming applications

00:14:56.690 --> 00:15:00.240
network conditions can
have a very big impact

00:15:00.240 --> 00:15:02.900
on the quality of service.

00:15:02.900 --> 00:15:04.880
And network conditions can vary.

00:15:04.880 --> 00:15:08.160
It not only varies from
connection to connection, even

00:15:08.160 --> 00:15:10.750
within a single connection
the network condition

00:15:10.750 --> 00:15:13.590
can vary significantly
over time.

00:15:13.590 --> 00:15:17.910
To cope with network condition
variations, what we do

00:15:17.910 --> 00:15:23.060
is we adapt the video
quality in real time,

00:15:23.060 --> 00:15:25.290
to the live network conditions.

00:15:25.290 --> 00:15:28.480
For example, we adapt
the video bit rate

00:15:28.480 --> 00:15:31.210
from around one megabits
per second all the way

00:15:31.210 --> 00:15:33.940
to more than five
megabits per second.

00:15:33.940 --> 00:15:37.440
And similarly, we also
adapt the video frame rate

00:15:37.440 --> 00:15:41.840
from around 15 frames per
second to the regular 60 frames

00:15:41.840 --> 00:15:44.300
per second.

00:15:44.300 --> 00:15:47.900
We also adapt a level of
protection against packet loss,

00:15:47.900 --> 00:15:52.000
based on how lossy the
network is in real time.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:54.500
